      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1fc5944887661110",
      "text": "We call non-text paragraphs \"items\" but they work the same way. When the Federated Wiki client hits an \"image\" item, it calls the image processing code, and produces the image from the encoded data in that page item. The image is not an embedded object. It's not a reference to a resource elsewhere. It's actually code stored on the page, which follows the page when you fork it."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "980a02d10df44f64",
      "text": "The same goes for numerical data. A comma separated datasource on a page is just as draggable and copyable as a paragraph, even though it is parsed as data. Another example - the ByteBeat plugin is a novelty, but shows how audio can be an output of a plugin. The MathJax plugin shows how mathematical markup can produce a graphic representation of a formula."
